# [DMM](../wg/dmm.html)

**IETF 125 - Distributed Mobility Management (DMM) Working Group Minutes**

## Summary
The DMM working group met at IETF 125 to review the status of active drafts and discuss updates to the mobile traffic steering architecture. The session was chaired by Sri Gundavelli and Satoru Matsushima, with John Kaippallimalil assisting as local chair. Luis M. Contreras served as the note-taker. Key highlights included the advancement of the MUP architecture toward AD review and a detailed presentation on the evolution of the Mobile Traffic Steering (MTS) framework.

## WG Status
**Slides:** [Working Group Status](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dmm-working-group-status-01)

*   **[draft-ietf-dmm-mup-architecture](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-dmm-mup-architecture/):** Satoru Matsushima reported that the document is ready for AD review and will be sent to the IESG soon. He noted that the architecture has seen successful commercial deployment by a major mobile operator in Japan. 
*   **[draft-ietf-dmm-srv6mob-arch](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-dmm-srv6mob-arch/):** This draft has expired. Satoru Matsushima noted that updates are needed based on deployment feedback, with plans to refresh the document before the next IETF meeting.
*   **[draft-ietf-dmm-mts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-dmm-mts/):** The draft was adopted as a working group document late last year and is currently being updated.

## Key Discussion Points

### Mobile Traffic Steering
**Presenter:** Marco Liebsch
**Slides:** [Mobile Traffic Steering](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dmm-mobile-traffic-steering-00)

Marco Liebsch presented the updates in [draft-ietf-dmm-mts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-dmm-mts/).

*   **Document Status:** Version 01 was published in February, addressing editorial clarifications and adding content regarding node ephemorality (specifically for Non-Terrestrial Networks/NTN).
*   **Architectural Models:** The draft explores two deployment options: a dedicated controller (centralized) and a decentralized control plane. Section 6 describes proactive, reactive, and hybrid operational modes.
*   **Information Model:** The current version includes a rough information model in the appendix. The authors propose evolving this into an Entity-Relationship Diagram (ERD) to better define traffic descriptors, path identifiers, and user plane anchor IDs.
*   **3GPP Alignment:** There is an ongoing discussion regarding whether the draft should include an application example specifically for 3GPP's next-generation user plane evolution.

**Discussion:**
*   **John Kaippallimalil** raised questions regarding flexibility and reselection. Specifically, he asked how the system handles multiple flows within a session and which flows are prioritized during a relocation/reallocation of a data plane node. 
*   **Marco Liebsch** clarified that the Mobile Communication System (MCS) makes the decision to change the user plane anchor. The MTS API's role is to notify the transport network of these changes to ensure optimized routing. 
*   **John Kaippallimalil** suggested that the assumption of per-flow vs. per-user granularity needs to be made explicit in the draft, as different models may exist in future evolutions.

